# Remove generated test artifacts when a spec is deleted — Architecture doc Section 7.1
#
# Trigger concept: the PRD names "SpecRegistry/delete" but no such concept exists in the codebase.
# Spec-lifecycle events are managed by the Resource concept (repertoire/concepts/codegen/resource.concept)
# which tracks input resources (files, configs) for generation pipelines. Resource/remove fires when
# a locator is removed from tracking — semantically equivalent to "a spec was deleted" for the
# purposes of this pipeline. The `locator` field maps to the same path value used as `sourceRef`
# in InvariantParser rows and TestArtifact rows, so TestArtifact/prune can match by spec identity.
#
# Resource/remove returns two variants that both use the `ok` name but with different output fields
# (an existing-record return and a not-found return). The when-clause matches on the
# `resource: ?r` output field which is only present when an actual record was removed; the
# not-found variant carries only `locator: ?loc` and will not match, which is the correct
# semantics — no artifacts to prune if no resource was tracked.

sync PruneArtifactsOnSpecDelete [eager]
  purpose {
    When a spec resource is removed from tracking via Resource/remove, clean up all
    generated TestArtifact rows for that spec so stale test files do not accumulate.
  }
when {
  Resource/remove: [ locator: ?loc ]
    => ok(resource: ?r)
}
then {
  TestArtifact/prune: [
    spec: ?loc
  ]
}
